[{"id":"VR854687","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">Show all your work for each part of the question. The parts within the question may not have equal weight.</p><br/><div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"Figure 1 shows an object far to the left of a concave lens. The object extends to a height uppercase H above the principle axis of the lens. The object is a horizontal distance uppercase D to the left of the lens. Two focal points are indicated on the principle axis, such that there is one point just to the left of the lens and one point just to the right of the lens. Each point is a horizontal distance of f from the lens. A ray extends downward and to the right from the top of the object, through the center of the mirror, and ends in bottom right portion of the figure. A note indicates that the figure is not drawn to scale.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR854687.g01.svg\"/></div>\n<p class=\"passage_para\">An object of height <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase H\"><math alttext=\"uppercase H\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>H</mi></math></span></span> above the principal axis is located to the left of a concave lens, as shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>. The distance from the lens to its focal point is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"f\"><math alttext=\"f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>f</mi></math></span></span>, and the distance from the lens to the object is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase D\"><math alttext=\"uppercase D\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>D</mi></math></span></span>, where <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase D is greater than f\"><math alttext=\"uppercase D is greater than f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>D</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>f</mi></math></span></span>. Also shown in Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> is a ray originating from the top of the object and directed toward the center of the lens.</p>\n</div></div></div></div><div class=\"item_part part_id:Ai part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Ai\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a)</p><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">i. On Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>, <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">draw</span> the following.</p></li></ul><ul class=\"unordered_list style:1\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">One additional ray, originating from the top of the object, that can be used to find the location of the image formed by the lens</p></li><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">An arrow that represents the location, height, and orientation of the image</p></li></ul></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR854687_rubric"},{"id":"VR854687","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:Aii part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"Aii\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The concave lens is removed and replaced with another lens, Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, which is convex and has the same distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"f\"><math alttext=\"f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>f</mi></math></span></span> to its focal point as the original lens. The object is still located a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase D\"><math alttext=\"uppercase D\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>D</mi></math></span></span> to the left of the lens.</p><ul class=\"unordered_list style:2\"><li class=\"list_item\"><p class=\"list_paragraph\">ii. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Derive</span> an expression for the magnitude of the height of the image formed by the lens. Express your answer in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase H\"><math alttext=\"uppercase H\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>H</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase D\"><math alttext=\"uppercase D\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>D</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"f\"><math alttext=\"f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>f</mi></math></span></span>, and physical constants, as appropriate.</p></li></ul><p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">Note:</span> If you need to draw anything other than what you have shown in part (a)(i) to assist in your solution, use the space below. Do NOT add anything to Figure <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR854687_rubric"},{"id":"VR854687","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b)</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> is now replaced with Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>. Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> is convex and the same size and shape as Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, but it is made of a material with an index of refraction that is greater than the refractive index of the material in Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>. <span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Indicate</span> where the image formed by Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> will be located compared to the image formed by Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>. Assume that the image is formed on the same side of the lens for both Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> and Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span>.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">_____ The image is at the same location for both lenses.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">_____ The image is closer to the lens for Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> than it was for Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">_____ The image is farther from the lens for Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> than it was for Lens <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\"><span class=\"formatted_text font_weight:bold\">Justify</span> your answer using physics principles.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR854687_rubric"}]